'''Garak''' was a [[dragonkin]] who was known to have destroyed a number of small settlements near the border of the [[Wilderness]]{{CitePostbag|issue=20|author=Achietties|letter=Letter 5}} during the [[Dragonkin Conflicts]] in the [[Fourth Age]]. A common misconception exists in which Garak was a particularly ferocious [[Dragon (race)|dragon]]; this is due to Archibald Malore's translations that standardised the poems describing it and being written as being a dragon.{{CiteNPC|npc=The truth behind the myth (excerpt)|quote=It wasn't until Archibald Malore's translation into the common tongue that all [of the original Camorra poems] were standardised and Garak became a 'dragon'.}}

[[Camorra Shayzien]], a little-known heroine from the time, slayed Garak, and it is this act that places her among the most famous heroes of the period, such as [[Arrav]] and [[Robert the Strong]].{{CiteNPC|npc=The truth behind the myth (excerpt)|quote=It is curious how, deposit all her other impressive accomplishments, it is the slaying of [Garak] that is considered to be Camorra's defining heroic feat. It is for this single act that she is counted among Arrav or Robert the Strong...}}

==Draconic nature==
A book titled [[The truth behind the myth (excerpt)|The Truth Behind the Myth]] questions the reason in which the slaying of Garak (who is referred in the book as a dragon) was considered as Camorra's defining heroic feat, rather than her cooperation with Robert the Strong should be far more impressive, and presents some hypotheses to help explain why this is the case.{{CiteNPC|npc=The truth behind the myth (excerpt)|quote=...her cooperation with [Robert the Strong] should, by all accounts, be far more impressive [than slaying Garak].}}

The first hypothesis considers the fact that humans, at the time, did not have the means to protect themselves from [[dragonfire]]. This is debunked by the fact that no other dragon from the time period had gained the reputation that Garak has, and historical records would likely have other examples of ferocious dragons.{{CiteNPC|npc=The truth behind the myth (excerpt)|quote=...no other dragon from this time period appears to have gained the legendary reputation that Garak has. If dragons were such an immense threat, then surely the historical record would have countless similar examples.}}

The second hypothesis considers Garak to be an exceptionally intelligent dragon, who is notorious enough to have been given a name (that does not correspond with any known human language), and that it may have been able to control its instinctual rage that most other dragons, despite their developed brains, are incapable of controlling.{{CiteNPC|npc=The truth behind the myth (excerpt)|quote=Examination of dragon corpses has shown that dragons possess remarkably developed brains. However, most dragons appear to be gripped by an instinctual rage and ferocity that makes them unable to utilise it to its full potential.}} The author debunks this hypothesis as it hinges on the assumption that the dragon named itself, and it is just as likely that the language went extinct.

The last hypothesis considers that Garak may not have been a dragon at all.{{CiteNPC|npc=The truth behind the myth (excerpt)|quote=...examining the original Camorra poems shows that there is actually very little evidence for Garek having been a dragon.}} Examining the original poems written on Camorra around 400 years after her death, refer to Garak as either a "fire serpent/reptile/snake" or a "fire bird/vulture", where the words of the original language have multiple meanings. While the author is not prepared to answer what Garak actually was, the descriptions of the original poems suggest that Garak was actually a [[dragonkin]].

